# TypeScript Best Practices

## Strict Mode Rules

This project uses TypeScript strict mode. Follow these guidelines:

### No `any`

Never use `any`. Use proper types or `unknown` with type guards.

```typescript
// Wrong
function process(data: any) { ... }

// Correct
function process(data: unknown) {
  if (typeof data === 'string') { ... }
}
```

### Define Interfaces Inline

Define interfaces in the file that uses them, not in separate type files.

```typescript
// In component file
interface Props {
  title: string;
  items: string[];
}
```

### Props Destructuring

Always destructure props with proper typing:

```typescript
// Astro
interface Props {
  post: CollectionEntry<'posts'>;
}
const { post } = Astro.props;

// React
interface Props {
  active: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
}
export default function Button({ active, onClick }: Props) { ... }
```

### Return Types

Add explicit return types for exported functions:

```typescript
export function formatDate(date: Date): string {
  return date.toLocaleDateString();
}
```

### Nullish Coalescing

Prefer `??` over `||` for fallbacks when `0` or `''` are valid values:

```typescript
// Correct - preserves 0 and ''
const count = input ?? 1;

// Wrong - treats 0 as falsy
const count = input || 1;
```

### Optional Chaining

Use optional chaining for potentially undefined values:

```typescript
const url = project.frontmatter.url;
```
